EP  - 77
PY  - 1992
DA  - 1992/01/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(92)90029-Q
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030440769290029Q
AB  - We introduce a semiparametric median regression approach to ordered discrete responses, generalizing the maximum score estimation of Manski (1985) for binary response. The identification and a.s. consistency are proved. We assume that there exists a latent continuous variable, and several variations of the median regression approach depending on the restriction on the thresholds for the latent variable are examined. For some cases, bounds for the scale are derived. We also derive bounds for the finite sample breakdown point of the median regression method to show its robustness.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - On the power function of the Durbin-Watson test
AU  - Bartels, Robert
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 51
IS  - 1
SP  - 101
EP  - 112
PY  - 1992
DA  - 1992/01/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(92)90031-L
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030440769290031L
AB  - Recent papers have drawn attention to the fact that the power function of the Durbin-Watson (DW) test against the alternative of a stationary first-order autoregression, is not necessarily monotonic as p departs from the null hypothesis that p = 0. Indeed for some data sets the power tends to 0 as p →±1, making inferences based on the DW test meaningless. The purpose of the present study is twofold. First, the paper provides new insight into the factors underlying this worrisome aspect of the DW power function and shows that it is not restricted to stationary processes. Second, the paper presents a fairly easily calculated boundary power function which for any given data set gives some guidance as to whether or not the DW test will have poor power properties.
ER  - 

